Yes, you could use any XML generator. Clojure has several, including an &lt;a href=&quot;http://github.com/antoniogarrote/clj-haml/tree/master&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;implementation of Haml&lt;/a&gt; and my own &lt;a href=&quot;http://github.com/richhickey/clojure-contrib/blob/master/src/clojure/contrib/prxml.clj#L142&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;prxml&lt;/a&gt;.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Andy B. wrote: <em>&#8220;using an xml templating engine like Haml might make editing the pom files even more palatable.&#8221;</em></p>
<p>Yes, you could use any XML generator. Clojure has several, including an <a href="http://github.com/antoniogarrote/clj-haml/tree/master" rel="nofollow">implementation of Haml</a> and my own <a href="http://github.com/richhickey/clojure-contrib/blob/master/src/clojure/contrib/prxml.clj#L142" rel="nofollow">prxml</a>.</p>
